Review this C++ event-handler code for memory safety. It crashes intermittently in production under load. Identify the bug class and rewrite with modern C++.

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <cstdlib>

struct Handler {
    virtual void on_event() = 0;
    virtual ~Handler() {}
};

struct LogHandler : Handler {
    void on_event() override { /* log */ }
};

std::vector<Handler*> g_handlers;

void register_handler() {
    Handler* h = new LogHandler();
    g_handlers.push_back(h);
}

void unregister_handler(Handler* h) {
    delete h;   // freed here
    // but h is still in g_handlers — dangling pointer!
}

void fire_events() {
    for (auto* h : g_handlers) {
        h->on_event();  // may dereference freed memory
    }
}
```

## Vulnerability: CWE-416 Use-After-Free + CWE-825 Expired Pointer Dereference

### Root cause
`unregister_handler` calls `delete h` but does **not** remove `h` from `g_handlers`. The raw pointer in the vector becomes a dangling pointer. When `fire_events()` iterates and calls `h->on_event()`, it dereferences freed heap memory. The C++ standard classifies this as Undefined Behaviour; in practice it causes heap corruption, vtable pointer corruption (exploitable for type-confusion / virtual dispatch hijack), or SIGSEGV. CERT C++ MEM50-CPP: *Do not access freed memory.*

### Why Rust eliminates this class by construction
Rust's ownership/borrow checker makes it a **compile-time error** to hold a reference to an object after its owner drops it. There is no raw pointer arithmetic by default; `Arc<Mutex<T>>` or `Weak<T>` patterns make shared ownership explicit. The equivalent Rust code would not compile if you tried to read from the freed handler.

### NEVER DO THIS
```cpp
delete h;            // freed
// h still lives in g_handlers as dangling pointer → UB on next fire
```

### Fixed — `shared_ptr` ownership + `weak_ptr` in registry
```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <memory>
#include <algorithm>
#include <cassert>

struct Handler {
    virtual void on_event() = 0;
    virtual ~Handler() = default;
};

struct LogHandler : Handler {
    void on_event() override { /* log */ }
};

// ── Registry holds weak_ptr so it does NOT extend object lifetime.
// When the caller drops their shared_ptr the weak_ptr expires safely.
std::vector<std::weak_ptr<Handler>> g_handlers;

// ── Returns shared_ptr; caller owns the lifetime.
std::shared_ptr<Handler> register_handler() {
    auto h = std::make_shared<LogHandler>();
    g_handlers.push_back(h);   // stores weak reference
    return h;                  // caller holds the strong ref
}

// ── 'Unregister' is just dropping the shared_ptr on the caller side.
// The weak_ptr in g_handlers will expire automatically; no manual delete.
// Optionally compact the registry:
void purge_expired() {
    g_handlers.erase(
        std::remove_if(g_handlers.begin(), g_handlers.end(),
                       [](const std::weak_ptr<Handler>& wp) {
                           return wp.expired();
                       }),
        g_handlers.end());
}

void fire_events() {
    for (auto& wp : g_handlers) {
        // ── lock() returns nullptr if the object was already destroyed
        if (auto h = wp.lock()) {
            h->on_event();   // safe: shared_ptr keeps alive for this call
        }
        // else: silently skip expired handlers
    }
}
```

### Why this is safe
| Pattern | Guarantee |
|---|---|
| `shared_ptr` ownership | Object destroyed exactly once when last strong ref drops |
| `weak_ptr` in registry | Registry can't prevent destruction; no dangling raw pointer |
| `wp.lock()` before use | Returns `nullptr` atomically if expired; never dereferences freed memory |
| `make_shared` | Single allocation; no naked `new`; exception safe |

**Rust note:** The equivalent safe Rust would use `Arc<dyn Handler>` + `Weak<dyn Handler>`—the borrow checker enforces the same discipline at compile time rather than via runtime refcounting.

**References:** CERT C++ MEM50-CPP, MEM51-CPP; CWE-416; MISRA C++:2023 Rule 21.6.2.

